-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Northern Nigeria Cement, KenolKobil Are Active
-- B y   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-09-24T14:41:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-24/sub-saharan-african-stocks-northern-nigeria-cement-kenolkobil-are-active.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  had a fifth day of decreases, slumping 0.1 percent
to 22,689.09 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to data
from the bourse’s website.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  retreated for a second day,
dropping 0.7 percent to 1,766.53 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis. Kenya’s  All-Share Index  fell 0.1 percent to 82.89 by the
close at 3 p.m. in Nairobi, a second day of declines. The  Ghana
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  declined the most since July 13,
slipping 2.1 percent to 6,702.81 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra.
Namibia’s exchange was closed for a public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Cement Co. of Northern Nigeria Plc  (CCNN NL), a producer of
the building material, dropped 70 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 13.5
naira, the most in a month. Net income for the six months
through June fell 56 percent to 519.3 million naira ($3.4
million) from a year earlier, the company said in a statement
distributed today by the Nigerian Stock Exchange.  KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer, surged
the most since July, climbing 65 cents, or 6.9 percent to 10.10
shillings. The company signed a new transportation and storage
agreement with Kenya Pipeline Co. and welcomed an announcement
by the energy ministry yesterday stating it can access Kenya
Petroleum Refinery Ltd. and have its licenses reinstated,
Chairman  Jacob Segman  said in a statement e-mailed from Nairobi
today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
